::hero
# Documents you can read. Documents agents can edit.

Noma is a plain-text format for books, docs, research, dashboards, and webpages. Readable like Markdown, structured like data, renderable like HTML.

:::button{href="https://github.com/ferax564/noma"}
View on GitHub
:::
::

## What you get

::grid{columns=3}
:::card{title="Block-stable IDs" icon="anchor"}
Every important block has a stable ID. Agents edit specific blocks instead of rewriting whole files. No more diff churn.
:::

:::card{title="Typed semantics" icon="brain"}
Claims, evidence, risks, decisions, plots, datasets, agent tasks. Documents that know what their parts mean.
:::

:::card{title="Multi-format render" icon="layers"}
One source. HTML for the web, PDF for print, JSON for tools, deterministic LLM context for agents.
:::
::

## Compare

::tabs
:::card{title="Markdown"}
Great for prose. Weak for grids, cards, claims, plots, citations, and stable agent edits.
:::

:::card{title="HTML / MDX"}
Powerful but unreadable in source form. Hostile to non-developers.
:::

:::card{title="Noma"}
Reads like Markdown. Renders like HTML. Edits like data. Compiles to PDF and books.
:::
::

## Roadmap

::callout{tone="note"}
**v0.1 today** — parser, AST, HTML + LLM + JSON renderers, validator, CLI.
**Next** — PDF via Typst, VS Code extension, book manifests, agent patch protocol.
::
